# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gas-constant
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] In 2019, four of the seven SI base units specified in the International System of Quantities were redefined in terms of natural physical constants, rather than human artefacts such as the standard kilogram.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The second, metre, and candela had previously been redefined using physical constants.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The four new definitions aimed to improve the SI without changing the value of any units, ensuring continuity with existing measurements.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] In November 2018, the 26th General Conference on Weights and Measures (CGPM) unanimously approved these changes, which the International Committee for Weights and Measures (CIPM) had proposed earlier that year after determining that previously agreed conditions for the change had been met.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] These conditions were satisfied by a series of experiments that measured the constants to high accuracy relative to the old SI definitions, and were the culmination of decades of research.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The previous major change of the metric system occurred in 1960 when the International System of Units (SI) was formally published.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] At this time the metre was redefined: the definition was changed from the prototype of the metre to a certain number of wavelengths of a spectral line of a krypton-86 radiation, making it derivable from universal natural phenomena.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The kilogram remained defined by a physical prototype, leaving it the only artefact upon which the SI unit definitions depended.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] At this time the SI, as a coherent system, was constructed around seven *base units*, powers of which were used to construct all other units.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] With the 2019 redefinition, the SI is constructed around seven defining *constants*, allowing all units to be constructed directly from these constants.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The designation of base units is retained but is no longer essential to define the SI units.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The metric system was originally conceived as a system of measurement that was derivable from unchanging phenomena, but practical limitations necessitated the use of artefacts – the prototype of the metre and prototype of the kilogram – when the metric system was introduced in France in 1799.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The definitions of some units were defined by measurements that are difficult to precisely realise in a laboratory, such as the kelvin, which was defined in terms of the triple point of water.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] With the 2019 redefinition, the SI became wholly derivable from natural phenomena with most units being based on fundamental physical constants.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] A number of authors have published criticisms of the revised definitions; their criticisms include the premise that the proposal failed to address the impact of breaking the link between the definition of the dalton and the definitions of the kilogram, the mole, and the Avogadro constant.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The basic structure of the SI was developed over about 170 years between 1791 and 1960.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] Since 1960, technological advances have made it possible to address weaknesses in the SI such as the dependence on a physical artefact to define the kilogram.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] During the early years of the French Revolution, the leaders of the French National Constituent Assembly decided to introduce a new system of measurement that was based on the principles of logic and natural phenomena.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The metre was defined as one ten-millionth of the distance from the north pole to the equator and the kilogram as the mass of one thousandth of a cubic metre of pure water.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] Although these definitions were chosen to avoid ownership of the units, they could not be measured with sufficient convenience or precision to be of practical use.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] Instead, realisations were created in the form of the **mètre des Archives** and **kilogramme des Archives**, which were a "best attempt" at fulfilling these principles.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The 1st CGPM (1889) formally approved the use of 40 prototype metres and 40 prototype kilograms made by the British firm Johnson Matthey as the standards mandated by the Convention of the Metre.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] 6 and Kilogram KIII were designated as the international prototype of the metre and the kilogram, respectively; the CGPM retained other copies as working copies, and the rest were distributed to member states for use as their national prototypes.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] About once every 40 years, the national prototypes were compared with and recalibrated against the international prototype.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] In 1921 the Convention of the Metre was revised and the mandate of the CGPM was extended to provide standards for all units of measure, not just mass and length.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] In the ensuing years, the CGPM took on responsibility for providing standards of electrical current (1946), luminosity (1946), temperature (1948), time (1956), and molar mass (1971).
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The 9th CGPM in 1948 instructed the CIPM "to make recommendations for a single practical system of units of measurement, suitable for adoption by all countries adhering to the Metre Convention".
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The recommendations based on this mandate were presented to the 11th CGPM (1960), where they were formally accepted and given the name "**Système International d'Unités**" and its abbreviation "SI".
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The 17th CGPM (1983) replaced the 1960 definition of the metre with one based on the second by giving an exact definition of the speed of light in units of metres per second.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] Since their manufacture, drifts of up to 2×10−8 kilograms (20 μg) per year in the national prototype kilograms relative to the international prototype of the kilogram (IPK) have been detected.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] There was no way of determining whether the national prototypes were gaining mass or whether the IPK was losing mass.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] Newcastle University metrologist Peter Cumpson has since identified mercury vapour absorption or carbonaceous contamination as possible causes of this drift.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] At the 21st meeting of the CGPM (1999), national laboratories were urged to investigate ways of breaking the link between the kilogram and a specific artefact.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] Metrologists investigated several alternative approaches to redefining the kilogram based on fundamental physical constants.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] Among others, the Avogadro project and the development of the Kibble balance (known as the "watt balance" before 2016) promised methods of indirectly measuring mass with very high precision.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] These projects provided tools that enable alternative means of redefining the kilogram.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] A report published in 2007 by the Consultative Committee for Thermometry (CCT) to the CIPM noted that their current definition of temperature has proved to be unsatisfactory for temperatures below 20 K and for temperatures above 1300 K.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The committee took the view that the Boltzmann constant provided a better basis for temperature measurement than did the triple point of water because it overcame these difficulties.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] At its 23rd meeting (2007), the CGPM mandated the CIPM to investigate the use of natural constants as the basis for all units of measure rather than the artefacts that were then in use.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The following year this was endorsed by the International Union of Pure and Applied Physics (IUPAP).
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] At a meeting of the CCU held in Reading, United Kingdom, in September 2010, a resolution and draft changes to the SI brochure that were to be presented to the next meeting of the CIPM in October 2010 were agreed to in principle.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The CIPM meeting of October 2010 found "the conditions set by the General Conference at its 23rd meeting have not yet been fully met.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] For this reason the CIPM does not propose a revision of the SI at the present time".
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The CIPM, however, presented a resolution for consideration at the 24th CGPM (17–21 October 2011) to agree to the new definitions in principle, but not to implement them until the details had been finalised.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] This resolution was accepted by the conference, and in addition the CGPM moved the date of the 25th meeting forward from 2015 to 2014.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] At the 25th meeting on 18 to 20 November 2014, it was found that "despite [progress in the necessary requirements] the data do not yet appear to be sufficiently robust for the CGPM to adopt the revised SI at its 25th meeting", thus postponing the revision to the next meeting in 2018.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] Measurements accurate enough to meet the conditions were available in 2017 and the redefinition was adopted at the 26th CGPM (13–16 November 2018).
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] Following the successful 1983 redefinition of the metre in terms of an exact numerical value for the speed of light, the BIPM's Consultative Committee for Units (CCU) recommended and the BIPM proposed that four further constants of nature should be defined to have exact values.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] As part of the redefinition, the International Prototype of the Kilogram was retired and definitions of the kilogram, the ampere, and the kelvin were replaced.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] These changes have the effect of redefining the SI base units, though the definitions of the SI derived units in terms of the base units remain the same.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] Following the CCU proposal, the texts of the definitions of all of the base units were either refined or rewritten, changing the emphasis from explicit-unit-type to explicit-constant-type definitions.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] Explicit-unit definitions define a unit in terms of a specific example of that unit; for example, in 1324 Edward II defined the inch as being the length of three barleycorns, and from 1889 to 2019 the kilogram was defined as the mass of the International Prototype of the kilogram.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] In explicit-constant definitions, a constant of nature is given a specified value, and the definition of the unit emerges as a consequence; for example, in 2019, the speed of light was defined as exactly 299792458 metres per second.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The length of the metre could be derived because the second had been already independently defined.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The previous and 2019 definitions are given below.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The new definition of the second is effectively the same as the previous one, the only difference being that the conditions under which the definition applies are more rigorously defined.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The new definition of the metre is effectively the same as the previous one, the only difference being that the additional rigour in the definition of the second propagated to the metre.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The definition of the kilogram fundamentally changed from an artefact (the International Prototype of the Kilogram) to a constant of nature.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] Because the Planck constant relates photon energy to photon frequency, the new definition relates the kilogram to the mass equivalent of the energy of a photon at a specific frequency.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The definition of the ampere underwent a major revision.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] For illustration, this is equivalent to defining one coulomb to be an exact specified multiple of the elementary charge.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] Because the previous definition contains a reference to force, which has the dimensions MLT−2, it follows that in the previous SI the kilogram, metre, and second – the base units representing these dimensions – had to be defined before the ampere could be defined.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] Other consequences of the previous definition were that in SI the value of vacuum permeability (*μ*0) was fixed at exactly 4*π*×10−7 H⋅m−1.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] A consequence of the revised definition is that the ampere no longer depends on the definitions of the kilogram and the metre; it does, however, still depend on the definition of the second.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] In addition, the numerical values when expressed in SI units of the vacuum permeability, vacuum permittivity, and impedance of free space, which were exact before the redefinition, are subject to experimental error after the redefinition.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] For example, the numerical value of the vacuum permeability has a relative uncertainty equal to that of the experimental value of the fine-structure constant $\alpha$ .
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The CODATA 2018 value for the relative standard uncertainty of $\alpha$ is 1.6×10−10.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The definition of the kelvin underwent a fundamental change.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] Rather than using the triple point of water to fix the temperature scale, the new definition uses the energy equivalent as given by Boltzmann's equation.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The previous definition of the mole linked it to the kilogram.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The revised definition breaks that link by making a mole a specific number of entities of the substance in question.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] One consequence of this change is that the previously defined relationship between the mass of the 12C atom, the dalton, the kilogram, and the Avogadro constant is no longer exact.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The wording of the 9th SI Brochure implies that the first statement remains valid, which means the second is no longer exactly true.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The molar mass constant, while still with great accuracy remaining 1 g/mol, is no longer exactly equal to that.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The new definition of the candela is effectively the same as the previous definition as dependent on other base units, with the result that the redefinition of the kilogram and the additional rigour in the definitions of the second and metre propagate to the candela.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] All seven of the SI base units are defined in terms of defined constants and universal physical constants.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] Seven constants are needed to define the seven base units but there is not a direct correspondence between each specific base unit and a specific constant; except the second and the mole, more than one of the seven constants contributes to the definition of any given base unit.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] When the New SI was first designed, there were more than six suitable physical constants from which the designers could choose.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] For example, once length and time had been established, the universal gravitational constant *G* could, from a dimensional point of view, be used to define mass.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The physical constants were chosen on the basis of minimal uncertainty associated with measuring the constant and the degree of independence of the constant in respect of other constants that were being used.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] Much of the work done by the CIPM is delegated to consultative committees.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The CIPM Consultative Committee for Units (CCU) has made the proposed changes while other committees have examined the proposal in detail and have made recommendations regarding their acceptance by the CGPM in 2014.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] As of March 2011, the International Avogadro Coordination (IAC) group had obtained an uncertainty of 3.0×10−8 and NIST had obtained an uncertainty of 3.6×10−8 in their measurements.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] On 1 September 2012 the European Association of National Metrology Institutes (EURAMET) launched a formal project to reduce the relative difference between the Kibble balance and the silicon sphere approach to measuring the kilogram from (17±5)×10−8 to within 2×10−8.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] As of the 2014 CODATA-recommended values of the fundamental physical constants published in 2016 using data collected until the end of 2014, all measurements met the CGPM's requirements, and the redefinition and the next CGPM quadrennial meeting in late 2018 could now proceed.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The vote, which was held on 16 November 2018 at the 26th CGPM, was unanimous; all attending national representatives voted in favour of the revised proposal.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The new definitions became effective on 20 May 2019.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The changes proposed in the new SI only addressed problems with the definition of the base units, including new definitions of the candela and the mole – units Foster argued are not true base units.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] Other issues raised by Foster fell outside the scope of the proposal.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] Concerns have been expressed that the use of explicit-constant definitions of the unit being defined that are not related to an example of its quantity will have many adverse effects.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] When the scale of the divergence between the IPK and national kilogram prototypes was reported in 2005, a debate began about whether the kilogram should be defined in terms of the mass of the silicon-28 atom or by using the Kibble balance.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] If the mass of a silicon atom were to be determined by the Avogadro project using the Avogadro constant, it could be linked directly to the kilogram.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] Concerns that the authors of the proposal had failed to address the impact of breaking the link between the mole, kilogram, dalton, and the Avogadro constant (*N*A) have also been expressed.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] This direct link has caused many to argue that the mole is not a true physical unit but, according to the Swedish philosopher Johansson, a "scaling factor".
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The 8th edition of the SI Brochure defined the dalton in terms of the mass of an atom of 12C.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] It defined the Avogadro constant in terms of this mass and the kilogram, making it determined by experiment.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The redefinition fixes the Avogadro constant and the 9th SI Brochure retains the definition of dalton in terms of 12C, with the effect that the link between the dalton and the kilogram will be broken.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] In 1993, the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) approved the use of the dalton as an alternative name for the unified atomic mass unit with the qualification that the CGPM had not given its approval.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] This would result in the dalton and the atomic mass unit potentially differing from each other with a relative uncertainty of the order of 10−10.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The 9th SI Brochure, however, defines both the dalton (Da) and the unified atomic mass unit (u) as exactly ⁠1/12⁠ of the mass of a free carbon-12 atom and not in relation to the kilogram, with the effect that the above equation will be inexact.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] Different temperature ranges need different measurement methods.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] Room temperature can be measured by means of expansion and contraction of a liquid in a thermometer but high temperatures are often associated with colour of blackbody radiation.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] Chyla, approaching the structure of SI from a philosophical point of view in the *Journal of the Polish Physical Society*, argued that temperature is not a real base unit but is an average of the thermal energies of the individual particles that comprise the body concerned.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] Chyla acknowledged, however, that in the macroscopic world, temperature plays the role of a base unit because much of the theory of thermodynamics is based on temperature.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] The Consultative Committee for Thermometry, part of the International Committee for Weights and Measures, publishes a *mise en pratique* (practical technique), last updated in 1990, for measuring temperature.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] At very low and at very high temperatures it often links energy to temperature via the Boltzmann constant.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] Foster argued that "luminous intensity [the candela] is not a physical quantity, but a photobiological quantity that exists in human perception", questioning whether the candela should be a base unit.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] Before the 1979 decision to define photometric units in terms of luminous flux (power) rather than luminous intensities of standard light sources, there was already doubt whether there should still be a separate base unit for photometry.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] Furthermore, there was unanimous agreement that the lumen was now more fundamental than the candela.
[src:gas-constant/2019-revision-of-the-si] However, for the sake of continuity the candela was kept as base unit.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] In chemistry, the **amount of substance** (symbol n) in a given sample of matter is defined as a ratio (*n* = *N*/*N*A) between the number of elementary entities (N) and the Avogadro constant (*N*A).
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] It is one of the seven base quantities of the International System of Units, SI.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] The unit of amount of substance in the SI is the mole (symbol: **mol**), a base unit.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] Since 2019, the mole has been defined such that the value of the Avogadro constant *N*A is exactly 6.02214076×1023 mol−1, defining a macroscopic unit convenient for use in laboratory-scale chemistry.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] The elementary entities are usually molecules, atoms, ions, or ion pairs of a specified kind.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] The particular substance sampled may be specified using a subscript or in parentheses, e.g., the amount of sodium chloride (NaCl) could be denoted as *n*NaCl or *n*(NaCl).
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] Sometimes, the amount of substance is referred to as the **chemical amount** or, informally, as the "**number of moles**" in a given sample of matter.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] The latter term is deprecated by the IUPAC because, for a substance X, the correct meaning of "number of moles" is *n*(X)/mol.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] The amount of substance in a sample can be calculated from measured quantities, such as mass or volume, given the molar mass of the substance or the molar volume of an ideal gas at a given temperature and pressure.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] Because of the way the mole and the dalton are defined, the mass in grams of one mole of a chemical compound is numerically very nearly equal to the mass of one molecule or formula unit of the compound in daltons.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] For example, a single molecule of water has a mass of about 18.0153 daltons on average, whereas a mole of water (which contains 6.02214076×1023 water molecules) has a mass of about 18.0153 grams on average.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] The molar mass of an isotope in grams per mole is approximately equal to the mass number.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] Before the mole was redefined in 2019, this equality was exact by definition for carbon-12.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] In chemistry, because of the law of multiple proportions, it is often more convenient to work with amounts of substances denominated in moles, than with masses (grams) or volumes (liters).
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] For example, the chemical fact "1 molecule of oxygen (O 2) will react with 2 molecules of hydrogen (H 2) to make 2 molecules of water (H2O)" can also be stated as "1 mole of O2 will react with 2 moles of H2 to form 2 moles of water".
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] The same chemical fact, expressed in terms of masses, would be "32.0 g of oxygen (1 mole of O 2) will react with approximately 4.0 g hydrogen (2 moles of H 2) to make approximately 36.0 g of water (2 moles of H2O)" (and the numbers would depend on the isotopic composition of the reagents).
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] In terms of volume, the numbers would depend on the pressure and temperature of the reagents and products, although the volume of an ideal gas is proportional to the amount in moles or number of molecules at constant temperature and pressure.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] For the same reasons, the concentrations of reagents and products in solution are often specified in moles per liter, rather than grams per liter.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] The amount of substance is also a convenient concept in thermodynamics.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] For example, the pressure of a certain quantity of a noble gas in a recipient of a given volume, at a given temperature, is directly related to the number of molecules in the gas (through the ideal gas law), not to its mass.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] This technical sense of the term "amount of substance" should not be confused with the general sense of "amount" in the English language.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] The latter may refer to other measurements such as mass or volume, rather than the number of particles.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] There are proposals to replace "amount of substance" with more easily distinguishable terms, such as **enplethy** and **stoichiometric amount**.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] The IUPAC recommends that "amount of substance" should be used instead of "number of moles", just as the quantity mass should not be called "number of (kilo)grams".
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] To avoid ambiguity, the nature of the particles should be specified in any measurement of the amount of substance: thus, a sample of 1 mol *of molecules* of oxygen (O 2) has a mass of about 32.00 g, whereas a sample of 1 mol *of atoms* of oxygen (O) has a mass of about 16.00 g.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] The quotient of some extensive physical quantity of a homogeneous sample by its amount of substance is an intensive property of the substance, usually named by the prefix "molar" or the suffix "per mole".
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] For example, the quotient of the mass of a sample by its amount of substance is its molar mass, for which the SI unit kilogram per mole or gram per mole may be used.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] This is about 18.015 g/mol for water, and 55.845 g/mol for iron.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] Similarly for volume, one gets the molar volume, which is about 18.069 millilitres per mole for liquid water and 7.092 mL/mol for iron at room temperature.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] From the heat capacity, one gets the molar heat capacity, which is about 75.385 J/(K⋅mol) for water and about 25.10 J/(K⋅mol) for iron.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] The molar mass ( M ) of a substance is the ratio of the mass ( m ) of a sample of that substance to its amount of substance ( n ): $M=m/n$ .
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] For most practical purposes, the numerical value of the molar mass in grams per mole is the same as that of the mean mass of one molecule or formula unit of the substance in daltons, as the mole was historically defined such that the molar mass constant was exactly 1 g/mol.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] Thus, given the molecular mass or formula mass in daltons, the same number in grams gives an amount very close to the mass of one mole of the substance.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] For example, the average molecular mass of water is about 18.015 Da and the molar mass of water is about 18.015 g/mol.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] This allows for accurate determination of the amount in moles of a substance by measuring its mass and dividing by the molar mass of the compound: $n=m/M$ .
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] For example, a mass of 100 g of water corresponds to an amount of about 5.5509 mol of water.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] The molar mass of a substance depends not only on its molecular formula, but also on the distribution of isotopes of each chemical element present in it.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] For example, the molar mass of calcium-40 is 39.96259098(22) g/mol, whereas the molar mass of calcium-42 is 41.95861801(27) g/mol, and of calcium with the normal isotopic mix is 40.078(4) g/mol.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] Other methods of determining the amount of substance include the use of the molar volume ( $V_{m}$ ) for ideal gases at a given temperature T and pressure P (through the relationship $V_{m}=V/n=RT/P$ ) or the measurement of electric charge (using Faraday's laws of electrolysis).
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] For example, the molar volume of an ideal gas under standard conditions of 0 °C (273.15 K) and 1 atm (101.325 kPa) is about 22.414 L/mol, and 1 m3 of an ideal gas under the same conditions is about 44.615 mol of gas.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] The standard SI unit of this quantity is mol/m3, although more practical units are commonly used, such as mole per liter (mol/L, equivalent to mol/dm3).
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] For example, the amount concentration of sodium chloride in ocean water is typically about 0.599 mol/L.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] The denominator is the volume of the solution, not of the solvent.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] Thus, for example, one liter of standard vodka contains about 0.40 L of ethanol (315 g, 6.85 mol) and 0.60 L of water.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] The amount concentration of ethanol is therefore (6.85 mol of ethanol)/(1 L of vodka) = 6.85 mol/L, not (6.85 mol of ethanol)/(0.60 L of water), which would be 11.4 mol/L.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] In chemistry, it is customary to read the unit "mol/L" as **molar**, and denote it by the symbol "M" (both following the numeric value).
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] Thus, for example, each liter of a "0.5 molar" or "0.5 M" solution of urea (CH 4N 2O) in water contains 0.5 moles of that molecule.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] By extension, the amount concentration is also commonly called the **molarity** of the substance of interest in the solution.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] However, as of May 2007, these terms and symbols are not condoned by IUPAC.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] This quantity should not be confused with the mass concentration, which is the mass of the substance of interest divided by the volume of the solution (about 35 g/L for sodium chloride in ocean water).
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] In a mixture of gases, the partial pressure of each component is proportional to its molar fraction.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] The alchemists, and especially the early metallurgists, probably had some notion of amount of substance, but there are no surviving records of any generalization of the idea beyond a set of recipes.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] In 1758, Mikhail Lomonosov questioned the idea that mass was the only measure of the quantity of matter, but he did so only in relation to his theories on gravitation.
[src:gas-constant/amount-of-substance] The development of the concept of amount of substance was coincidental with, and vital to, the birth of modern chemistry.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Nearly all argon in Earth's atmosphere is radiogenic argon-40, derived from the decay of potassium-40 in Earth's crust.
[src:gas-constant/argon] In the universe, argon-36 is by far the most common argon isotope, as it is the most easily produced by stellar nucleosynthesis in supernovas.
[src:gas-constant/argon] The name "argon" is derived from the Ancient Greek word ἀργόν, neuter singular form of ἀργός meaning 'lazy' or 'inactive', as a reference to the fact that the element undergoes almost no chemical reactions.
[src:gas-constant/argon] The complete octet (eight electrons) in the outer atomic shell makes argon stable and resistant to bonding with other elements.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Its triple point temperature of 83.8058 K is a defining fixed point in the International Temperature Scale of 1990.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon is extracted industrially by the fractional distillation of liquid air.
[src:gas-constant/argon] It is mostly used as an inert shielding gas in welding and other high-temperature industrial processes where ordinarily unreactive substances become reactive; for example, an argon atmosphere is used in graphite electric furnaces to prevent the graphite from burning.
[src:gas-constant/argon] It is also used in incandescent and fluorescent lighting, and other gas-discharge tubes.
[src:gas-constant/argon] It makes a distinctive blue-green gas laser.
[src:gas-constant/argon] It is also used in fluorescent glow starters.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon has approximately the same solubility in water as oxygen and is 2.5 times more soluble in water than nitrogen.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon is colorless, odorless, nonflammable and nontoxic as a solid, liquid or gas.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon is chemically inert under most conditions and forms no confirmed stable compounds at room temperature.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Although argon is a noble gas, it can form some compounds under various extreme conditions.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon fluorohydride (HArF), a compound of argon with fluorine and hydrogen that is stable below 17 K (−256.1 °C; −429.1 °F), has been demonstrated.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Although the neutral ground-state chemical compounds of argon are presently limited to HArF, argon can form clathrates with water when atoms of argon are trapped in a lattice of water molecules.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Ions, such as ArH+ , and excited-state complexes, such as ArF, have been demonstrated.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Theoretical calculation predicts several more argon compounds that should be stable but have not yet been synthesized.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon was first isolated from air in 1894 by Lord Rayleigh and Sir William Ramsay at University College London by removing oxygen, carbon dioxide, water, and nitrogen from a sample of clean air.
[src:gas-constant/argon] They first accomplished this by replicating an experiment of Henry Cavendish's.
[src:gas-constant/argon] The arc was powered by a battery of five Grove cells and a Ruhmkorff coil of medium size.
[src:gas-constant/argon] The alkali absorbed the oxides of nitrogen produced by the arc and also carbon dioxide.
[src:gas-constant/argon] They operated the arc until no more reduction of volume of the gas could be seen for at least an hour or two and the spectral lines of nitrogen disappeared when the gas was examined.
[src:gas-constant/argon] The remaining oxygen was reacted with alkaline pyrogallate to leave behind an apparently non-reactive gas which they called argon.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Before isolating the gas, they had determined that nitrogen produced from chemical compounds was 0.5% lighter than nitrogen from the atmosphere.
[src:gas-constant/argon] The difference was slight, but it was important enough to attract their attention for many months.
[src:gas-constant/argon] They concluded that there was another gas in the air mixed in with the nitrogen.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon was also encountered in 1882 through independent research of H.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Each observed new lines in the emission spectrum of air that did not match known elements.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Prior to 1957, the symbol for argon was "A".
[src:gas-constant/argon] This was changed to Ar after the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry published the work *Nomenclature of Inorganic Chemistry* in 1957.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon constitutes 0.934% by volume and 1.288% by mass of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Air is the primary industrial source of purified argon products.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon is isolated from air by fractionation, most commonly by cryogenic fractional distillation, a process that also produces purified nitrogen, oxygen, neon, krypton and xenon.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Earth's crust and seawater contain 1.2 ppm and 0.45 ppm of argon, respectively.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Naturally occurring 40 K, with a half-life of 1.25×109 years, decays to stable 40 Ar (11.2%) by electron capture or positron emission, and also to stable 40 Ca (88.8%) by beta decay.
[src:gas-constant/argon] These properties and ratios are used to determine the age of rocks by K–Ar dating.
[src:gas-constant/argon] In Earth's atmosphere, 39 Ar is made by cosmic ray activity, primarily by neutron capture of 40 Ar followed by two-neutron emission.
[src:gas-constant/argon] In the subsurface environment, it is also produced through neutron capture by 39 K, followed by proton emission.
[src:gas-constant/argon] 37 Ar is created from the neutron capture by 40 Ca followed by an alpha particle emission as a result of subsurface nuclear explosions.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Between locations in the Solar System, the isotopic composition of argon varies greatly.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Where the major source of argon is the decay of 40 K in rocks, 40 Ar will be the dominant isotope, as it is on Earth.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon produced directly by stellar nucleosynthesis is dominated by the alpha-process nuclide 36 Ar.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Correspondingly, solar argon contains 84.6% 36 Ar (according to solar wind measurements), and the ratio of the three isotopes 36Ar : 38Ar : 40Ar in the atmospheres of the outer planets is 8400 : 1600 : 1.
[src:gas-constant/argon] This contrasts with the low abundance of primordial 36 Ar in Earth's atmosphere, which is only 31.5 ppmv (= 9340 ppmv × 0.337%), comparable with that of neon (18.18 ppmv) on Earth and with interplanetary gasses, measured by probes.
[src:gas-constant/argon] The atmospheres of Mars, Mercury and Titan (the largest moon of Saturn) contain argon, predominantly as 40 Ar.
[src:gas-constant/argon] The predominance of radiogenic 40 Ar is the reason the standard atomic weight of terrestrial argon is greater than that of the next element, potassium, a fact that was puzzling when argon was discovered.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Mendeleev positioned the elements on his periodic table in order of atomic weight, but the inertness of argon suggested a placement *before* the reactive alkali metal.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Henry Moseley later solved this problem by showing that the periodic table is actually arranged in order of atomic number (see History of the periodic table).
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon's complete octet of electrons indicates full s and p subshells.
[src:gas-constant/argon] This full valence shell makes argon very stable and extremely resistant to bonding with other elements.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Before 1962, argon and the other noble gases were considered to be chemically inert and unable to form compounds; however, compounds of the heavier noble gases have since been synthesized.
[src:gas-constant/argon] The first argon compound with tungsten pentacarbonyl, W(CO)5Ar, was isolated in 1975.
[src:gas-constant/argon] However, it was not widely recognised at that time.
[src:gas-constant/argon] In August 2000, another argon compound, argon fluorohydride (HArF), was formed by researchers at the University of Helsinki, by shining ultraviolet light onto frozen argon containing a small amount of hydrogen fluoride with caesium iodide.
[src:gas-constant/argon] This discovery caused the recognition that argon could form weakly bound compounds, even though it was not the first.
[src:gas-constant/argon] It is stable up to 17 kelvins (−256 °C).
[src:gas-constant/argon] The metastable ArCF2+ 2 dication, which is valence-isoelectronic with carbonyl fluoride and phosgene, was observed in 2010.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon-36, in the form of argon hydride (argonium) ions, has been detected in interstellar medium associated with the Crab Nebula supernova; this was the first noble-gas molecule detected in outer space.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Solid argon hydride (Ar(H2)2) has the same crystal structure as the MgZn2 Laves phase.
[src:gas-constant/argon] It forms at pressures between 4.3 and 220 GPa, though Raman measurements suggest that the H2 molecules in Ar(H2)2 dissociate above 175 GPa.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon is extracted industrially by the fractional distillation of liquid air in a cryogenic air separation unit; a process that separates liquid nitrogen, which boils at 77.3 K, from argon, which boils at 87.3 K, and liquid oxygen, which boils at 90.2 K.
[src:gas-constant/argon] About 700,000 tonnes of argon are produced worldwide every year.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Other noble gases would be equally suitable for most of these applications, but argon is by far the cheapest.
[src:gas-constant/argon] It is inexpensive, since it occurs naturally in air and is readily obtained as a byproduct of cryogenic air separation in the production of liquid oxygen and liquid nitrogen: the primary constituents of air are used on a large industrial scale.
[src:gas-constant/argon] The other noble gases (except helium) are produced this way as well, but argon is the most plentiful by far.
[src:gas-constant/argon] The bulk of its applications arise simply because it is inert and relatively cheap.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon is used in some high-temperature industrial processes where ordinarily non-reactive substances become reactive.
[src:gas-constant/argon] For example, an argon atmosphere is used in graphite electric furnaces to prevent the graphite from burning.
[src:gas-constant/argon] For some of these processes, the presence of nitrogen or oxygen gases might cause defects within the material.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon is used in some types of arc welding such as gas metal arc welding and gas tungsten arc welding, as well as in the processing of titanium and other reactive elements.
[src:gas-constant/argon] An argon atmosphere is also used for growing crystals of silicon and germanium.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon is used in the poultry industry to asphyxiate birds, either for mass culling following disease outbreaks, or as a means of slaughter more humane than electric stunning.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon is denser than air and displaces oxygen close to the ground during inert gas asphyxiation.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Its non-reactive nature makes it suitable in a food product, and since it replaces oxygen within the dead bird, argon also enhances shelf life.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon is sometimes used for extinguishing fires where valuable equipment may be damaged by water or foam.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Liquid argon is used as the target for neutrino experiments and direct dark matter searches.
[src:gas-constant/argon] The interaction between the hypothetical WIMPs and an argon nucleus produces scintillation light that is detected by photomultiplier tubes.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Two-phase detectors containing argon gas are used to detect the ionized electrons produced during the WIMP–nucleus scattering.
[src:gas-constant/argon] As with most other liquefied noble gases, argon has a high scintillation light yield (about 51 photons/keV), is transparent to its own scintillation light, and is relatively easy to purify.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Compared to xenon, argon is cheaper and has a distinct scintillation time profile, which allows the separation of electronic recoils from nuclear recoils.
[src:gas-constant/argon] On the other hand, its intrinsic beta-ray background is larger due to 39 Ar contamination, unless one uses argon from underground sources, which has much less 39 Ar contamination.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Most of the argon in Earth's atmosphere was produced by electron capture of long-lived 40 K (40 K + e− → 40 Ar + ν) present in natural potassium within Earth.
[src:gas-constant/argon] The 39 Ar activity in the atmosphere is maintained by cosmogenic production through the knockout reaction 40 Ar(n,2n)39 Ar and similar reactions.
[src:gas-constant/argon] The half-life of 39 Ar is only 269 years.
[src:gas-constant/argon] As a result, the underground Ar, shielded by rock and water, has much less 39 Ar contamination.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Dark-matter detectors currently operating with liquid argon include DarkSide, WArP, ArDM, microCLEAN and DEAP.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Neutrino experiments include ICARUS and MicroBooNE, both of which use high-purity liquid argon in a time projection chamber for fine grained three-dimensional imaging of neutrino interactions.
[src:gas-constant/argon] At Linköping University, Sweden, the inert gas is being utilized in a vacuum chamber in which plasma is introduced to ionize metallic films.
[src:gas-constant/argon] This process results in a film usable for manufacturing computer processors.
[src:gas-constant/argon] The new process would eliminate the need for chemical baths and use of expensive, dangerous and rare materials.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon is used to displace oxygen- and moisture-containing air in packaging material to extend the shelf-lives of the contents (argon has the European food additive code E938).
[src:gas-constant/argon] Aerial oxidation, hydrolysis, and other chemical reactions that degrade the products are retarded or prevented entirely.
[src:gas-constant/argon] High-purity chemicals and pharmaceuticals are sometimes packed and sealed in argon.
[src:gas-constant/argon] In winemaking, argon is used in a variety of activities to provide a barrier against oxygen at the liquid surface, which can spoil wine by fueling both microbial metabolism (as with acetic acid bacteria) and standard redox chemistry.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon is sometimes used as the propellant in aerosol cans.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon is also used as a preservative for such products as varnish, polyurethane, and paint, by displacing air to prepare a container for storage.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Since 2002, the American National Archives stores important national documents such as the Declaration of Independence and the Constitution within argon-filled cases to inhibit their degradation.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon is preferable to the helium that had been used in the preceding five decades, because helium gas escapes through the intermolecular pores in most containers and must be regularly replaced.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon may be used as the inert gas within Schlenk lines and gloveboxes.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon is preferred to less expensive nitrogen in cases where nitrogen may react with the reagents or apparatus.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon may be used as the carrier gas in gas chromatography and in electrospray ionization mass spectrometry; it is the gas of choice for the plasma used in ICP spectroscopy.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon is preferred for the sputter coating of specimens for scanning electron microscopy.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon gas is also commonly used for sputter deposition of thin films as in microelectronics and for wafer cleaning in microfabrication.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Cryosurgery procedures such as cryoablation use liquid argon to destroy tissue such as cancer cells.
[src:gas-constant/argon] It is used in a procedure called "argon-enhanced coagulation", a form of argon plasma beam electrosurgery.
[src:gas-constant/argon] The procedure carries a risk of producing gas embolism and has resulted in the death of at least one patient.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Blue argon lasers are used in surgery to weld arteries, destroy tumors, and correct eye defects.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon has also been used experimentally to replace nitrogen in the breathing or decompression mix known as Argox, to speed the elimination of dissolved nitrogen from the blood.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Incandescent lights are filled with argon, to preserve the filaments at high temperature from oxidation.
[src:gas-constant/argon] It is used for the specific way it ionizes and emits light, such as in plasma globes and calorimetry in experimental particle physics.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Gas-discharge lamps filled with pure argon provide lilac/violet light; with argon and some mercury, blue light.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon is also used for blue and green argon-ion lasers.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon is used for thermal insulation in energy-efficient windows.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon is also used in technical scuba diving to inflate a dry suit because it is inert and has low thermal conductivity.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon is used as a propellant in the development of the Variable Specific Impulse Magnetoplasma Rocket (VASIMR).
[src:gas-constant/argon] Compressed argon gas is allowed to expand, to cool the seeker heads of some versions of the AIM-9 Sidewinder missile and other missiles that use cooled thermal seeker heads.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon-39, with a half-life of 269 years, has been used for a number of applications, primarily ice core and ground water dating.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Also, potassium–argon dating and related argon-argon dating are used to date sedimentary, metamorphic, and igneous rocks.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Argon has been used by athletes as a doping agent to simulate hypoxic conditions.
[src:gas-constant/argon] In 2014, the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) added argon and xenon to the list of prohibited substances and methods, although at this time there is no reliable test for abuse.
[src:gas-constant/argon] Although argon is non-toxic, it is 38% more dense than air and therefore considered a dangerous asphyxiant in closed areas.
[src:gas-constant/argon] It is difficult to detect because it is colorless, odorless, and tasteless.
[src:gas-constant/argon] A 1994 incident, in which a man was asphyxiated after entering an argon-filled section of oil pipe under construction in Alaska, highlights the dangers of argon tank leakage in confined spaces and emphasizes the need for proper use, storage and handling.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] In physical chemistry, the **Arrhenius equation** is a formula for the temperature dependence of reaction rates.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] This equation has a vast and important application in determining the rate of chemical reactions and for calculation of energy of activation.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] Arrhenius provided a physical justification and interpretation for the formula.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] Currently, it is best seen as an empirical relationship.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] It can be used to model the temperature variation of diffusion coefficients, population of crystal vacancies, creep rates, and many other thermally induced processes and reactions.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] The Eyring equation, developed in 1935, also expresses the relationship between rate and energy.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] The temperature dependence arises because a greater fraction of molecular collisions have sufficient energy to exceed the activation barrier as temperature increases.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] The only difference is the unit of *E*a: the former form uses energy per mole, which is common in chemistry, while the latter form uses energy per molecule directly, which is common in physics.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] The different units are accounted for in using either the gas constant, R, or the Boltzmann constant, *k*B, as the multiplier of temperature T.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] The unit of the pre-exponential factor A are identical to those of the rate constant and will vary depending on the order of the reaction.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] If the reaction is first order it has the unit inverse second, s−1, and for that reason it is often called the *frequency factor* or *attempt frequency* of the reaction.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] It can be seen that either increasing the temperature or decreasing the activation energy (for example through the use of catalysts) will result in an increase in rate of reaction.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] Given the small temperature range of kinetic studies, it is reasonable to approximate the activation energy as being independent of the temperature.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] With this equation it can be roughly estimated that the rate of reaction increases by a factor of about 2 to 3 for every 10 °C rise in temperature, for common values of activation energy and temperature range.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] The ${\textstyle \exp {\left({\frac {-E_{\mathrm {a} }}{RT}}\right)}}$ factor denotes the fraction of molecules with energy greater than or equal to ⁠ $E_{\mathrm {a} }$ ⁠.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] where $\Delta U^{0}$ denotes the apposite standard internal energy change value.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] where $E_{\text{f}}$ and $E_{\text{b}}$ are the activation energies associated with the forward and backward reactions respectively, with ⁠ $\Delta U^{0}=E_{\text{f}}-E_{\text{b}}$ ⁠.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] This has the same form as an equation for a straight line: $y=ax+b,$ where ⁠ x ⁠ is the reciprocal of ⁠ T ⁠.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] So, when a reaction has a rate constant obeying the Arrhenius equation, a plot of ⁠ $\ln {k}$ ⁠ versus ⁠ $T^{-1}$ ⁠ gives a straight line, whose slope and intercept can be used to determine ⁠ $E_{\mathrm {a} }$ ⁠ and ⁠ A ⁠ respectively.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] This procedure is common in experimental chemical kinetics.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] The modified Arrhenius equation makes explicit the temperature dependence of the pre-exponential factor.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] The original Arrhenius expression above corresponds to ⁠ $n=0$ ⁠.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] Fitted rate constants typically lie in the range ⁠ $-1<n<1$ ⁠.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] Theoretical analyses yield various predictions for ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] It has been pointed out that "it is not feasible to establish, on the basis of temperature studies of the rate constant, whether the predicted ⁠ $T^{1/2}$ ⁠ dependence of the pre-exponential factor is observed experimentally".
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] However, if additional evidence is available, from theory and/or from experiment (such as density dependence), there is no obstacle to incisive tests of the Arrhenius law.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] Another common modification is the stretched exponential form $k=A\exp \left[-\left({\frac {E_{a}}{RT}}\right)^{\beta }\right],$ where ⁠ $\beta$ ⁠ is a dimensionless number of order 1.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] This is typically regarded as a purely empirical correction or *fudge factor* to make the model fit the data, but can have theoretical meaning, for example showing the presence of a range of activation energies or in special cases like the Mott variable range hopping.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] Arrhenius argued that for reactants to transform into products, they must first acquire a minimum amount of energy, called the activation energy ⁠ $E_{\mathrm {a} }$ ⁠.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] At an absolute temperature ⁠ T ⁠, the fraction of molecules that have a kinetic energy greater than ⁠ $E_{\mathrm {a} }$ ⁠ can be calculated from statistical mechanics.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] This fraction increases with temperature because molecular energies follow a Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution, which broadens as ⁠ T ⁠ rises and increases the proportion of molecules with kinetic energies equal to or greater than the activation energy.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] The concept of *activation energy* explains the exponential nature of the relationship, and in one way or another, it is present in all kinetic theories.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] From a physical perspective, activation energy represents an energy barrier that must be overcome for reactant molecules to reach a transition state.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] Increasing temperature raises the fraction of molecules with sufficient kinetic energy to overcome this barrier, which explains the strong temperature dependence of reaction rates described by the Arrhenius equation.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] One approach is the collision theory of chemical reactions, developed by Max Trautz and William Lewis in the years 1916–18.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] In this theory, molecules are supposed to react if they collide with a relative kinetic energy along their line of centers that exceeds ⁠ $E_{\mathrm {a} }$ ⁠.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] The rate constant is then calculated as ⁠ $\textstyle k=z_{AB}\exp {\frac {-E_{\mathrm {a} }}{RT}}$ ⁠, so that the collision theory predicts that the pre-exponential factor is equal to the collision number ⁠ $z_{AB}$ ⁠.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] However for many reactions this agrees poorly with experiment, so the rate constant is written instead as ⁠ $\textstyle k=\rho z_{AB}\exp {\frac {-E_{\mathrm {a} }}{RT}}$ ⁠.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] Here ⁠ $\rho$ ⁠ is an empirical steric factor, often much less than 1.00, which is interpreted as the fraction of sufficiently energetic collisions in which the two molecules have the correct mutual orientation to react.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] The Eyring equation, another Arrhenius-like expression, appears in the "transition state theory" of chemical reactions, formulated by Eugene Wigner, Henry Eyring, Michael Polanyi and M.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] At first sight this looks like an exponential multiplied by a factor that is *linear* in temperature.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] However, free energy is itself a temperature-dependent quantity.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] The free energy of activation $\Delta G^{\ddagger }=\Delta H^{\ddagger }-T\Delta S^{\ddagger }$ is the difference of an enthalpy term and an entropy term multiplied by the absolute temperature.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] The pre-exponential factor depends primarily on the entropy of activation.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] The overall expression again takes the form of an Arrhenius exponential (of enthalpy rather than energy) multiplied by a slowly varying function of ⁠ T ⁠.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] The precise form of the temperature dependence depends upon the reaction, and can be calculated using formulas from statistical mechanics involving the partition functions of the reactants and of the activated complex.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] Both the Arrhenius activation energy and the rate constant ⁠ k ⁠ are experimentally determined, and represent macroscopic reaction-specific parameters that are not simply related to threshold energies and the success of individual collisions at the molecular level.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] Consider a particular collision (an elementary reaction) between molecules ⁠ A ⁠ and ⁠ B ⁠.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] The collision angle, the relative translational energy, the internal (particularly vibrational) energy will all determine the chance that the collision will produce a product molecule ⁠ $AB$ ⁠.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] Macroscopic measurements of ⁠ E ⁠ and ⁠ k ⁠ are the result of many individual collisions with differing collision parameters.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] To probe reaction rates at molecular level, experiments are conducted under near-collisional conditions and this subject is often called molecular reaction dynamics.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] Another situation where the explanation of the Arrhenius equation parameters falls short is in heterogeneous catalysis, especially for reactions that show Langmuir-Hinshelwood kinetics.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] Clearly, molecules on surfaces do not "collide" directly, and a simple molecular cross-section does not apply here.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] Instead, the pre-exponential factor reflects the travel across the surface towards the active site.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] There are deviations from the Arrhenius law during the glass transition in all classes of glass-forming matter.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] The Arrhenius law predicts that the motion of the structural units (atoms, molecules, ions, etc.) should slow down at a slower rate through the glass transition than is experimentally observed.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] In other words, the structural units slow down at a faster rate than is predicted by the Arrhenius law.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] This observation is made reasonable assuming that the units must overcome an energy barrier by means of a thermal activation energy.
[src:gas-constant/arrhenius-equation] The thermal energy must be high enough to allow for translational motion of the units which leads to viscous flow of the material.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The **atmosphere of Earth** consists of a layer of mixed gas (commonly referred to as **air**) that is retained by gravity, surrounding the Earth's surface.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] It contains variable quantities of suspended aerosols and particulates that create weather features such as clouds and hazes.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The atmosphere serves as a protective buffer between the Earth's surface and outer space.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] It shields the surface from most meteoroids and ultraviolet solar radiation, reduces diurnal temperature variation – the temperature extremes between day and night, and keeps it warm through heat retention via the greenhouse effect.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The atmosphere redistributes heat and moisture among different regions via air currents, and provides the chemical and climate conditions that allow life to exist and evolve on Earth.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] By mole fraction (i.e., by quantity of molecules), dry air contains 78.08% nitrogen, 20.95% oxygen, 0.93% argon, 0.04% carbon dioxide, and small amounts of other trace gases (see Composition below for more detail).
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Air also contains a variable amount of water vapor, on average around 1% at sea level, and 0.4% over the entire atmosphere.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Earth's primordial atmosphere consisted of gases accreted from the solar nebula, but the composition changed significantly over time, affected by many factors such as volcanism, outgassing, impact events, weathering and the evolution of life (particularly the photoautotrophs).
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] In the present day, human activity has contributed to atmospheric changes, such as climate change (mainly through deforestation and fossil-fuel–related global warming), ozone depletion and acid deposition.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The atmosphere has a mass of about 5.15×1018 kg, three quarters of which is within about 11 km (6.8 mi; 36,000 ft) of the surface.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The atmosphere becomes thinner with increasing altitude, with no definite boundary between the atmosphere and outer space.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The Kármán line at 100 km (62 mi) is often used as a conventional definition of the edge of space.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Several layers can be distinguished in the atmosphere based on characteristics such as temperature and composition, namely the troposphere, stratosphere, mesosphere, thermosphere (formally the ionosphere), and exosphere.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Air composition, temperature and atmospheric pressure vary with altitude.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Air suitable for use in photosynthesis by terrestrial plants and respiration of terrestrial animals is found within the troposphere.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The study of Earth's atmosphere and its processes is called atmospheric science (aerology), and includes multiple subfields, such as climatology and atmospheric physics.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Early pioneers in the field include Léon Teisserenc de Bort and Richard Assmann.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The study of the historic atmosphere is called paleoclimatology.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The three major constituents of Earth's atmosphere are nitrogen, oxygen, and argon.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Water vapor accounts for roughly 0.25% of the atmosphere by mass.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The remaining gases are often referred to as trace gases, among which are other greenhouse gases, principally carbon dioxide, methane, nitrous oxide, and ozone.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Besides argon, other noble gases, neon, helium, krypton, and xenon are also present.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Filtered air includes trace amounts of many other chemical compounds.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Many substances of natural origin may be present in locally and seasonally variable small amounts as aerosols in an unfiltered air sample, including dust of mineral and organic composition, pollen and spores, sea spray, and volcanic ash.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Various industrial pollutants also may be present as gases or aerosols, such as chlorine (elemental or in compounds), fluorine compounds, and elemental mercury vapor.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Sulfur compounds such as hydrogen sulfide and sulfur dioxide (SO2) may be derived from natural sources or from industrial air pollution.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The average molecular weight of dry air, which can be used to calculate densities or to convert between mole fraction and mass fraction, is about 28.946 or 28.964 g/mol.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] This is decreased when the air is humid.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Up to an altitude of around 100 km (62 mi), atmospheric turbulence mixes the component gases so that their relative concentrations remain the same.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] There exists a transition zone from roughly 80 to 120 km (50 to 75 mi) where this turbulent mixing gradually yields to molecular diffusion.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The latter process forms the heterosphere where the relative concentration of lighter gases increase with altitude.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] In general, air pressure and density decrease with altitude in the atmosphere.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] However, temperature has a more complicated profile with altitude and may remain relatively constant or even increase with altitude in some regions (see the temperature section).
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Because the general pattern of the temperature/altitude profile, or lapse rate, is constant and measurable by means of instrumented balloon soundings, the temperature behavior provides a useful metric to distinguish atmospheric layers.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The exosphere is the outermost layer of Earth's atmosphere (though it is so tenuous that some scientists consider it to be part of interplanetary space rather than part of the atmosphere).
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] It extends from the thermopause (also known as the "exobase") at the top of the thermosphere to a poorly defined boundary with the solar wind and interplanetary medium.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The altitude of the exobase varies from about 500 kilometres (310 mi; 1,600,000 ft) to about 1,000 kilometres (620 mi) in times of higher incoming solar radiation.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The upper limit varies depending on the definition.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Various authorities consider it to end at about 10,000 kilometres (6,200 mi) or about 190,000 kilometres (120,000 mi)—about halfway to the moon, where the influence of Earth's gravity is about the same as radiation pressure from sunlight.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The geocorona visible in the far ultraviolet (caused by neutral hydrogen) extends to at least 100,000 kilometres (62,000 mi).
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] This layer is mainly composed of extremely low densities of hydrogen, with limited amounts of helium, carbon dioxide, and nascent oxygen closer to the exobase.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The atoms and molecules are so far apart that they can travel hundreds of kilometres without colliding with one another.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Thus, the exosphere no longer behaves like a gas, and the particles constantly escape into space.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] These free-moving particles follow ballistic trajectories and may migrate in and out of the magnetosphere or the solar wind.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Every second, the Earth loses about 3 kg of hydrogen, 50 g of helium, and much smaller amounts of other constituents.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The exosphere is too far above Earth for meteorological phenomena to be possible.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The exosphere contains many of the artificial satellites that orbit Earth.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The thermosphere is the second-highest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] It extends from the mesopause (which separates it from the mesosphere) at an altitude of about 80 km (50 mi) up to the thermopause at an altitude range of 500–1000 km (310–620 mi).
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The height of the thermopause varies considerably due to changes in solar activity.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The passage of the dusk and dawn solar terminator creates background density perturbations up to a factor of two through this layer, forming a dominant feature in this region.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Because the thermopause lies at the lower boundary of the exosphere, it is also referred to as the exobase.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Overlapping the thermosphere, from 50 to 600 kilometres (31 to 373 mi) above Earth's surface, is the ionosphere – a region of enhanced plasma density.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The temperature of the thermosphere gradually increases with height and can rise as high as 1500 °C (2700 °F), though the gas molecules are so far apart that its temperature in the usual sense is not very meaningful.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] This temperature increase is caused by absorption of ionizing UV and X-ray emission from the Sun.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The air is so rarefied that an individual molecule (of oxygen, for example) travels an average of 1 kilometre (0.62 mi; 3300 ft) between collisions with other molecules.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Although the thermosphere has a high proportion of molecules with high energy, it would not feel hot to a human in direct contact, because its density is too low to conduct a significant amount of energy to or from the skin.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] This layer is completely cloudless and free of water vapor.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] However, non-hydrometeorological phenomena such as the aurora borealis and aurora australis are occasionally seen in the thermosphere at an altitude of around 100 km (62 mi).
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The colors of the aurora are linked to the properties of the atmosphere at the altitude they occur.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The most common is the green aurora, which comes from atomic oxygen in the 1S state, and occurs at altitudes from 120 to 400 km (75 to 250 mi).
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The International Space Station orbits in the thermosphere, between 370 and 460 km (230 and 290 mi).
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] It is this layer where many of the satellites orbiting the Earth are present.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The mesosphere is the third highest layer of Earth's atmosphere, occupying the region above the stratosphere and below the thermosphere.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] It extends from the stratopause at an altitude of about 50 km (31 mi) to the mesopause at 80–85 km (50–53 mi) above sea level.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Temperatures drop with increasing altitude to the mesopause that marks the top of this middle layer of the atmosphere.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] It is the coldest place on Earth and has an average temperature around −85 °C (−120 °F; 190 K).
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Because the atmosphere absorbs sound waves at a rate that is proportional to the square of the frequency, audible sounds from the ground do not reach the mesosphere.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Infrasonic waves can reach this altitude, but they are difficult to emit at a high power level.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Just below the mesopause, the air is so cold that even the very scarce water vapor at this altitude can condense into polar-mesospheric noctilucent clouds of ice particles.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] These are the highest clouds in the atmosphere and may be visible to the naked eye if sunlight reflects off them about an hour or two after sunset or similarly before sunrise.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] They are most readily visible when the Sun is around 4 to 16 degrees below the horizon.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Lightning-induced discharges known as transient luminous events (TLEs) occasionally form in the mesosphere above tropospheric thunderclouds.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The mesosphere is also the layer where most meteors and satellites burn up upon atmospheric entrance.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] It is too high above Earth to be accessible to jet-powered aircraft and balloons, and too low to permit orbital spacecraft.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The mesosphere is mainly accessed by sounding rockets and rocket-powered aircraft.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The stratosphere is the second-lowest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] It lies above the troposphere and is separated from it by the tropopause.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] This layer extends from the top of the troposphere at roughly 12 km (7.5 mi) above Earth's surface to the stratopause at an altitude of about 50 to 55 km (31 to 34 mi).
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] 99% of the total mass of the atmosphere lies below 30 km (19 mi), and the atmospheric pressure at the top of the stratosphere is roughly 1/1000 the pressure at sea level.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] It contains the ozone layer, which is the part of Earth's atmosphere that contains relatively high concentrations of that gas.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The stratosphere defines a layer in which temperatures rise with increasing altitude.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] This rise in temperature is caused by the absorption of ultraviolet radiation (UV) from the Sun by the ozone layer, which restricts turbulence and mixing.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Although the temperature may be −80 °C (−110 °F; 190 K) at the tropopause, the top of the stratosphere is much warmer, and may be just below 0 °C.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] This layer is unique to the Earth; neither Mars nor Venus have a stratosphere because of low abundances of oxygen in their atmospheres.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The stratospheric temperature profile creates very stable atmospheric conditions, so the stratosphere lacks the weather-producing air turbulence that is so prevalent in the troposphere.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Consequently, the stratosphere is almost completely free of clouds and other forms of weather.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] However, polar stratospheric or nacreous clouds are occasionally seen in the lower part of this layer of the atmosphere where the air is coldest.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The stratosphere is the highest layer that can be accessed by jet-powered aircraft.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The troposphere is the lowest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] It extends from Earth's surface to an average height of about 12 km (7.5 mi), although this altitude varies from about 9 km (5.6 mi) at the geographic poles to 17 km (11 mi) at the Equator, with some variation due to weather.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The troposphere is bounded above by the tropopause, a boundary marked in most places by a temperature inversion (i.e. a layer of relatively warm air above a colder one), and in others by a zone that is isothermal with height.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Although variations do occur, the temperature usually declines with increasing altitude in the troposphere because the troposphere is mostly heated through energy transfer from the surface.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Thus, the lowest part of the troposphere (i.e.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Earth's surface) is typically the warmest section of the troposphere.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] This promotes vertical mixing (hence, the origin of its name in the Greek word τρόπος, *tropos*, meaning "turn").
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The troposphere contains roughly 80% of the mass of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The troposphere is denser than all its overlying layers because a larger atmospheric weight sits on top of the troposphere and causes it to be more severely compressed.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Fifty percent of the total mass of the atmosphere is located in the lower 5.5 km (3.4 mi) of the troposphere.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Nearly all atmospheric water vapor or moisture is found in the troposphere, so it is the layer where most of Earth's weather takes place.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The ability of the atmosphere to retain water decreases as the temperature declines, so 90% of the water vapor is held in the lower part of the troposphere.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] It has basically all the weather-associated cloud genus types generated by active wind circulation, although very tall cumulonimbus thunder clouds can penetrate the tropopause from below and rise into the lower part of the stratosphere.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Most conventional aviation activity takes place in the troposphere, and it is the only layer accessible by propeller-driven aircraft.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Contrails are formed from jet engine water emission at altitudes where the atmospheric temperature is about −53 °C (−63 °F); typically around 7.7 km (4.8 mi) for modern engines.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Above this altitude lies the heterosphere, which includes the exosphere and most of the thermosphere.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Here, the chemical composition varies with altitude.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] is large compared with the size of motions that cause mixing.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] with the heavier ones, such as oxygen and nitrogen, present only near the bottom of the heterosphere.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The upper part of the heterosphere is composed almost completely of hydrogen, the lightest element.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The average temperature of the atmosphere at Earth's surface is 14 °C (57 °F; 287 K) or 15 °C (59 °F; 288 K), depending on the reference.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The average atmospheric pressure at sea level is defined by the International Standard Atmosphere as 101325 pascals (760.00 Torr; 14.6959 psi; 760.00 mmHg).
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] This is sometimes referred to as a unit of standard atmospheres (atm).
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Total atmospheric mass is 5.1480×1018 kg (1.13494×1019 lb), about 2.5% less than would be inferred from the average sea-level pressure and Earth's area of 51007.2 megahectares, this portion being displaced by Earth's mountainous terrain.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Atmospheric pressure is the total weight of the air above unit area at the point where the pressure is measured.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Thus air pressure varies with location and weather.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Air pressure decreases exponentially with altitude at a rate that depends on the air temperature.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The rate of decrease is determined by a temperature-dependent parameter called the scale height: for each increase in altitude by this height, the pressure decreases by a factor of *e* (the base of natural logarithms, approximately 2.718).
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] For Earth, this value is typically 5.5 to 6 km for altitudes up to around 80 km (50 mi).
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] However, the atmosphere is more accurately modeled with a customized equation for each layer that takes gradients of temperature, molecular composition, solar radiation and gravity into account.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] At heights over 100 km, the atmosphere is not well mixed, so each chemical species has its own scale height.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] At altitudes of 200 to 300 km, the combined scale height is 20 to 30 km.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Even above the Kármán line, significant atmospheric effects such as auroras still occur.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Meteors begin to glow in this region, though the larger ones may not burn up until they penetrate more deeply.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The various layers of Earth's ionosphere, important to HF radio propagation, begin below 100 km and extend beyond 500 km.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] By comparison, the International Space Station typically orbit at 370–460 km, within the F-layer of the ionosphere, where they encounter enough atmospheric drag to require reboosts every few months, otherwise orbital decay will occur, resulting in a return to Earth.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Depending on solar activity, satellites can experience noticeable atmospheric drag at altitudes as high as 600–800 km.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Starting at sea level, the temperature decreases with altitude until reaching the stratosphere at around 11 km.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Above, the temperature stabilizes over a large vertical distance.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Starting above about 20 km, the temperature increases with height, due to heating within the ozone layer caused by the capture of significant ultraviolet radiation from the Sun by the molecular oxygen and ozone gas in this region.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] A second region of increasing temperature with altitude occurs at very high altitudes, in the aptly-named thermosphere above 90 km.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] During the night, the ground radiates more energy than it gains from the atmosphere.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] As energy is conducted from the nearby atmosphere to the cooler ground, it creates a temperature inversion where the local temperature increases with altitude up to around 1,000 m.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] For example, at sea level the speed of sound is 340 m/s.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] At the average temperature of the stratosphere, −60 °C, the speed of sound decreases to 290 m/s.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Density is not measured directly but is calculated from measurements of temperature, pressure and humidity using the equation of state for air (a form of the ideal gas law).
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Atmospheric density decreases as the altitude increases.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] This variation can be approximately modeled using the barometric formula.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] More sophisticated models are used to predict the orbital decay of satellites.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The average mass of the atmosphere is about 5 quadrillion (5×1015) tonnes or 1/1,200,000 the mass of Earth.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] According to the American National Center for Atmospheric Research, "The total mean mass of the atmosphere is 5.1480×1018 kg with an annual range due to water vapor of 1.2 or 1.5×1015 kg, depending on whether surface pressure or water vapor data are used; somewhat smaller than the previous estimate.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Solar radiation (or sunlight) is the energy Earth receives from the Sun.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Earth also emits radiation back into space, but at longer wavelengths that humans cannot see.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] As energy propagates through the atmosphere, it is impacted by the process of radiative transfer.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] That is, some of the incoming and emitted radiation is subject to absorption, emission, and scattering by the atmosphere.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Another portion of the incident energy is reflected, with the two most important atmospheric reflectors being dust and clouds.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Depending on the properties of the aerosol, clouds can reflect up to 70% of the incident radiation.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Globally, clouds reflect 20% of the incoming energy, contributing two thirds of the planet's total albedo.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] In May 2017, glints of light, seen as twinkling from an orbiting satellite a million miles away, were found to be reflected light from ice crystals in the troposphere.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] When light passes through Earth's atmosphere, photons interact with it through *scattering*.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] If the light does not interact with the atmosphere, it is called *direct radiation* and is what you see if you were to look directly at the Sun.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] *Indirect radiation* is light that has been scattered in the atmosphere.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] For example, on an overcast day when you cannot see your shadow, there is no direct radiation reaching you, it has all been scattered.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] As another example, due to a phenomenon called Rayleigh scattering, shorter (blue) wavelengths scatter more easily than longer (red) wavelengths.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] This is why the sky looks blue; you are seeing scattered blue light.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Because the Sun is close to the horizon, the Sun's rays pass through more atmosphere than normal before reaching your eye.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Much of the blue light has been scattered out, leaving the red light in a sunset.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Different molecules absorb different wavelengths of radiation.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] For example, O2 and O3 absorb almost all radiation with wavelengths shorter than 300 nanometres.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Water (H2O) absorbs at many wavelengths above 700 nm.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] When a molecule absorbs a photon, it increases the energy of the molecule.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] This heats the atmosphere, but the atmosphere also cools by emitting radiation, as discussed below.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] In astronomical spectroscopy, the absorption of specific frequencies by the atmosphere is referred to as telluric contamination.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The combined absorption spectra of the gases in the atmosphere leave "windows" of low opacity, allowing the transmission of only certain bands of light.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The optical window runs from around 300 nm (ultraviolet-C) up into the range humans can see, the visible spectrum (commonly called light), at roughly 400–700 nm and continues to the infrared to around 1100 nm.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] There are also infrared and radio windows that transmit some infrared and radio waves at longer wavelengths.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] For example, the radio window runs from about one centimetre to about eleven-metre waves.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Because of its temperature, the atmosphere emits infrared radiation.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] For example, on clear nights Earth's surface cools down faster than on cloudy nights.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] This is because clouds (H2O) are strong absorbers and emitters of infrared radiation.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] This is also why it becomes colder at night at higher elevations.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The greenhouse effect is directly related to this absorption and emission effect.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Some gases in the atmosphere absorb and emit infrared radiation, but do not interact in this manner with sunlight in the visible spectrum.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Common examples of these are CO2 and H2O.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Without greenhouse gases in the atmosphere, the average temperature of Earth's surface would be a frozen −18 °C (0 °F), rather than the present comfortable average of 15 °C (59 °F).
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The refractive index of air is close to, but just greater than, 1.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Systematic variations in the refractive index can lead to the bending of light rays over long optical paths.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] One example is that, under some circumstances, observers on board ships can see other vessels just over the horizon because light is refracted in the same direction as the curvature of Earth's surface.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The refractive index of air depends on temperature, giving rise to refraction effects when the temperature gradient is large.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] An example of such effects is the mirage.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The flow of air around the planet is divided into three main convection cells by latitude.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Around the equator, the Hadley cell is driven by the rising flow of air along the equator.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] In the upper atmosphere, this air flows toward the poles.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] At mid latitudes, this circulation is reversed, with ground air flowing toward the poles with the Ferrel cell.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Finally, in the high latitudes is the Polar cell, where air again rises and flows toward the poles.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The interface between these cells is responsible for jet streams.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] These are narrow, fast moving bands that flow from west to east and typically form at an elevation of around 9,100 m (30,000 ft).
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Jet streams can shift around depending on conditions.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] They are strongest in winter, when the boundaries between hot and cold air are the most pronounced.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] In the middle latitudes, it is instabilities in the jet streams that are responsible for moving weather systems.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] As with the oceans, the Earth's atmosphere is subject to waves and tidal forces.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] These are triggered by non-uniform heating by the Sun, and by the daily solar cycle, respectively.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Wave-like behavior can occur on a variety of scales, from smaller gravity waves that transfer momentum into the higher atmospheric layers, to much larger planetary waves, or Rossby waves.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Atmospheric tides are periodic oscillations of the troposphere and stratosphere that transport energy to the upper atmosphere.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The first atmosphere, during the Early Earth's Hadean eon, consisted of gases in the solar nebula, primarily hydrogen, and probably simple hydrides such as those now found in the gas giants (Jupiter and Saturn), notably water vapor, methane and ammonia.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] During this earliest era, the Moon-forming collision and numerous impacts with large meteorites heated the atmosphere, driving off the most volatile gases.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The collision with Theia, in particular, melted and ejected large portions of Earth's mantle and crust and outgassed significant amounts of steam which eventually cooled and condensed to contribute to ocean water at the end of the Hadean.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The increasing solidification of Earth's crust at the end of the Hadean closed off most of the advective heat transfer to the surface, causing the atmosphere to cool, which condensed most of the water vapor out of the air precipitating into a superocean.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Further outgassing from volcanism, supplemented by gases introduced by huge asteroids during the Late Heavy Bombardment, created the subsequent Archean atmosphere, which consisted largely of nitrogen plus carbon dioxide, methane and inert gases.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] A major part of carbon dioxide emissions dissolved in water and reacted with metals such as calcium and magnesium during weathering of crustal rocks to form carbonates that were deposited as sediments.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Water-related sediments have been found that date from as early as 3.8 billion years ago.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] About 3.4 billion years ago, nitrogen formed the major component of the then-stable "second atmosphere".
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The influence of the evolution of life has to be taken into account rather soon in the history of the atmosphere because hints of earliest life forms appeared as early as 3.5 billion years ago.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] How Earth at that time maintained a climate warm enough for liquid water and life, if the early Sun put out 30% lower solar radiance than today, is a puzzle known as the "faint young Sun paradox".
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The geological record however shows a continuous relatively warm surface during the complete early temperature record of Earth – with the exception of one cold glacial phase about 2.4 billion years ago.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] In the late Neoarchean, an oxygen-containing atmosphere began to develop, apparently due to a billion years of cyanobacterial photosynthesis (known as the Great Oxygenation Event), which have been found as stromatolite fossils from 2.7 billion years ago.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The early basic carbon isotopy (isotope ratio proportions) strongly suggests conditions similar to the current, and that the fundamental features of the carbon cycle became established as early as 4 billion years ago.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Ancient sediments in the Gabon dating from between about 2.15 and 2.08 billion years ago provide a record of Earth's dynamic oxygenation evolution.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] These fluctuations in oxygenation were likely driven by the Lomagundi-Jatuli Carbon Isotope Excursion.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The constant re-arrangement of continents by plate tectonics influences the long-term evolution of the atmosphere by transferring carbon dioxide to and from large continental carbonate stores.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Before this time, any oxygen produced by cyanobacterial photosynthesis would be readily removed by the oxidation of reducing substances on the Earth's surface, notably ferrous iron, sulfur and atmospheric methane.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Free oxygen molecules did not start to accumulate in the atmosphere until the rate of production of oxygen began to exceed the availability of reductant materials that removed oxygen.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] This point signifies a shift from a reducing atmosphere to an oxidizing atmosphere.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] O2 showed major variations during the Proterozoic, including a billion-year period of euxinia, until reaching a steady state of more than 15% by the end of the Precambrian.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The amount of oxygen in the atmosphere has fluctuated over the last 600 million years, reaching a peak of about 35% around 280 million years ago during the Carboniferous period, significantly higher than today's 21%.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Two main processes govern changes in the atmosphere: the evolution of plants and their increasing role in carbon fixation, and the consumption of oxygen by rapidly diversifying animal faunae and also by plants for photorespiration and their own metabolic needs at night.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Breakdown of pyrite and volcanic eruptions release sulfur into the atmosphere, which reacts and hence reduces oxygen in the atmosphere.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] However, volcanic eruptions also release carbon dioxide, which can fuel oxygenic photosynthesis by terrestrial and aquatic plants.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] The cause of the variation of the amount of oxygen in the atmosphere is not precisely understood.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Periods with more oxygen in the atmosphere were often associated with more rapid development of animals.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Since 1750, human activity, especially after the Industrial Revolution, has increased the concentrations of various greenhouse gases, most importantly carbon dioxide, methane and nitrous oxide.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] Greenhouse gas emissions, coupled with deforestation and destruction of wetlands via logging and land developments, have caused an observed rise in global temperatures, with the global average surface temperatures being 1.1 °C higher in the 2011–2020 decade than they were in 1850.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-of-earth] It has raised concerns of man-made climate change, which can have significant environmental impacts such as sea level rise, ocean acidification, glacial retreat (which threatens water security), increasing extreme weather events and wildfires, ecological collapse and mass dying of wildlife.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-unit] The **standard atmosphere** (symbol: **atm**) is a unit of pressure defined as 101325 Pa.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-unit] It is sometimes used as a *reference pressure* or *standard pressure*.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-unit] It is approximately equal to Earth's average atmospheric pressure at sea level.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-unit] The standard atmosphere was originally defined as the pressure exerted by a 760 mm column of mercury at 0 °C (32 °F) and standard gravity (*g*n = 9.80665 m/s2).
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-unit] It was used as a reference condition for physical and chemical properties, and the definition of the centigrade temperature scale set 100 °C as the boiling point of water at this pressure.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-unit] In 1954, the 10th General Conference on Weights and Measures (CGPM) adopted *standard atmosphere* for general use and affirmed its definition of being precisely equal to 1013250 dynes per square centimetre (101325 Pa).
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-unit] This defined pressure in a way that is independent of the properties of any particular substance.
[src:gas-constant/atmosphere-unit] The notation **ata** has been used to indicate an absolute pressure measured in either standard atmospheres (atm) or technical atmospheres (at).
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] Atomic mass is often measured in dalton (Da) (a.k.a. unified atomic mass unit (u)).
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] One dalton is equal to ⁠+1/12⁠ the mass of a carbon-12 atom in its natural state, given by the atomic mass constant *m*u = *m*(12C)/12 = 1 Da, where *m*(12C) is the atomic mass of carbon-12.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] Thus, the numerical value of the atomic mass of a nuclide when expressed in daltons is close to its mass number.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] The **relative isotopic mass** (see section below) can be obtained by dividing the atomic mass *m*a of an isotope by the atomic mass constant *m*u, yielding a dimensionless value.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] Thus, the atomic mass of a carbon-12 atom *m*(12C) is 12 Da by definition, but the relative isotopic mass of a carbon-12 atom *A*r(12C) is simply 12.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] The sum of *relative isotopic masses* of all atoms in a molecule is the *relative molecular mass*.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] The atomic mass of an isotope and the *relative isotopic mass* refers to a certain specific isotope of an element.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] Because substances are usually not isotopically pure, it is convenient to use the *elemental atomic mass* which is the average atomic mass of an element, weighted by the abundance of the isotopes.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] The dimensionless (standard) atomic weight is the weighted mean relative isotopic mass of a (typical naturally occurring) mixture of isotopes.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] Relative *isotopic* mass (a property of a single atom) is not to be confused with the averaged quantity atomic weight (see above), that is an average of values for many atoms in a given sample of a chemical element.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] While atomic mass is an absolute mass, relative isotopic mass is a dimensionless number with no units.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] This loss of units results from the use of a scaling ratio with respect to a carbon-12 standard, and the word "relative" in the term "relative isotopic mass" refers to this scaling *relative* to carbon-12.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] The relative isotopic mass, then, is the mass of a given isotope (specifically, any single nuclide), when this value is scaled by the mass of carbon-12, where the latter has to be determined experimentally.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] Equivalently, the relative isotopic mass of an isotope or nuclide is the mass of the isotope relative to ⁠+1/12⁠ of the mass of a carbon-12 atom.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] For example, the relative isotopic mass of a carbon-12 atom is exactly 12.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] For comparison, the atomic mass of a carbon-12 atom is exactly 12 daltons.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] Alternately, the atomic mass of a carbon-12 atom may be expressed in any other mass units: for example, the atomic mass of a carbon-12 atom is 1.99264688270(62)×10−26 kg.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] As is the case for the related *atomic mass* when expressed in daltons, the relative isotopic mass numbers of nuclides other than carbon-12 are not whole numbers, but are always close to whole numbers.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] The atomic mass or relative isotopic mass are sometimes confused, or incorrectly used, as synonyms of relative atomic mass (also known as atomic weight) or the standard atomic weight (a particular variety of atomic weight, in the sense that it is standardized).
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] However, as noted in the introduction, atomic mass is an absolute mass while all other terms are dimensionless.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] Relative atomic mass and standard atomic weight represent terms for (abundance-weighted) averages of relative atomic masses in elemental samples, not for single nuclides.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] Relative atomic mass and standard atomic weight will only be the same as the relative isotopic mass for elements with one stable isotope.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] The atomic mass (relative isotopic mass) is defined as the mass of a single atom, which is only one isotope (nuclide), and is not an abundance-weighted average, as in the case of relative atomic mass/atomic weight.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] For example, every atom of oxygen-16 has exactly the same atomic mass (relative isotopic mass).
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] For elements that have one naturally occurring isotope (mononuclidic elements) or one dominant isotope, the difference between the atomic mass of the most common isotope, and the (standard) relative atomic mass or (standard) atomic weight will be nil, or small enough to not effect most calculations.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] For elements with more than one isotope in significant quantities, the mass of individual atoms will be different from an average across all the isotopes.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] For elements that have more than one common isotope, the numerical difference in relative atomic mass (atomic weight) from even the most common relative isotopic mass, can be half a mass unit or more (e.g. see the case of chlorine where atomic weight and standard atomic weight are about 35.45).
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] The atomic mass (relative isotopic mass) of an uncommon isotope can differ from the relative atomic mass, atomic weight, or standard atomic weight, by several mass units.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] Any mass defect due to nuclear binding energy is experimentally a small fraction (less than 1%) of the mass of an equal number of free nucleons.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] When compared to the average mass per nucleon in carbon-12, which is moderately strongly bound compared with other atoms, the mass defect of binding for most atoms is an even smaller fraction of a dalton.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] Since free protons and neutrons differ from each other in mass by a small fraction of a dalton (1.38844933(49)×10−3 Da), rounding the relative isotopic mass, or the atomic mass of any given nuclide given in daltons to the nearest whole number, always gives the nucleon count, or mass number.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] Additionally, the neutron count (neutron number) may then be derived by subtracting the number of protons (atomic number) from the mass number (nucleon count).
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] The amount that the ratio of atomic masses to mass number deviates from 1 is as follows: the deviation starts positive at hydrogen-1, then decreases until it reaches a local minimum at helium-4.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] Isotopes of lithium, beryllium, and boron are less strongly bound than helium, as shown by their increasing mass-to-mass number ratios.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] This corresponds to the fact that nuclear fission in an element heavier than zirconium produces energy, and fission in any element lighter than niobium requires energy.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] On the other hand, nuclear fusion of two atoms of an element lighter than scandium (except for helium) produces energy, whereas fusion in elements heavier than calcium requires energy.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] The fusion of two atoms of 4He yielding beryllium-8 would require energy, and the beryllium would quickly fall apart again.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] 4He can fuse with tritium (3H) or with 3He; these processes occurred during Big Bang nucleosynthesis.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] The formation of elements with more than seven nucleons requires the fusion of three atoms of 4He in the triple-alpha process, skipping over lithium, beryllium, and boron to produce carbon-12.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] Direct comparison and measurement of the masses of atoms is achieved with mass spectrometry.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] One can calculate the molecular mass of a compound by adding the atomic masses (not the standard atomic weights) of its constituent atoms.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] Conversely, the molar mass is usually computed from the standard atomic weights (not the atomic or nuclide masses).
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] Thus, molecular mass and molar mass differ slightly in numerical value and represent different concepts.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] Molecular mass is the mass of a molecule, which is the sum of its constituent atomic masses.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] Molar mass is an average of the masses of the constituent molecules in a chemically pure but isotopically heterogeneous ensemble.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] In both cases, the multiplicity of the atoms (the number of times it occurs) must be taken into account, usually by multiplication of each unique mass by its multiplicity.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] The first scientists to determine relative atomic masses were John Dalton and Thomas Thomson between 1803 and 1805 and Jöns Jakob Berzelius between 1808 and 1826.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] Relative atomic mass (*Atomic weight*) was originally defined relative to that of the lightest element, hydrogen, which was taken as 1.00, and in the 1820s, Prout's hypothesis stated that atomic masses of all elements would prove to be exact multiples of that of hydrogen.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] Berzelius, however, soon proved that this was not even approximately true, and for some elements, such as chlorine, relative atomic mass, at about 35.5, falls almost exactly halfway between two integral multiples of that of hydrogen.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] Still later, this was shown to be largely due to a mix of isotopes, and that the atomic masses of pure isotopes, or nuclides, are multiples of the hydrogen mass, to within about 1%.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] In the 1860s, Stanislao Cannizzaro refined relative atomic masses by applying Avogadro's law (notably at the Karlsruhe Congress of 1860).
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] In the 20th century, until the 1960s, chemists and physicists used two different atomic-mass scales.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] The chemists used an "atomic mass unit" (amu) scale such that the natural mixture of oxygen isotopes had an atomic mass 16, while the physicists assigned the same number 16 to only the atomic mass of the most common oxygen isotope (16O, containing eight protons and eight neutrons).
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] However, because oxygen-17 and oxygen-18 are also present in natural oxygen this led to two different tables of atomic mass.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] The unified scale based on carbon-12, 12C, met the physicists' need to base the scale on a pure isotope, while being numerically close to the chemists' scale.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] This was adopted as the 'unified atomic mass unit'.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] The current International System of Units (SI) primary recommendation for the name of this unit is the dalton and symbol 'Da'.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] The name 'unified atomic mass unit' and symbol 'u' are recognized names and symbols for the same unit.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] The term *atomic weight* is being phased out slowly and being replaced by *relative atomic mass*, in most current usage.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] This shift in nomenclature reaches back to the 1960s and has been the source of much debate in the scientific community, which was triggered by the adoption of the unified atomic mass unit and the realization that weight was in some ways an inappropriate term.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] In 1979, as a compromise, the term "relative atomic mass" was introduced as a secondary synonym for atomic weight.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] Twenty years later the primacy of these synonyms was reversed, and the term "relative atomic mass" is now the preferred term.
[src:gas-constant/atomic-mass] However, the term "*standard* atomic weights" (referring to the standardized expectation atomic weights of differing samples) has not been changed, because simple replacement of "atomic weight" with "relative atomic mass" would have resulted in the term "standard relative atomic mass".
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] The **molar gas constant** (also known as the **gas constant**, **universal gas constant**, or **ideal gas constant**) is denoted by the symbol *R* or *R*.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] It is the molar equivalent to the Boltzmann constant, expressed in units of energy per temperature increment per amount of substance, rather than energy per temperature increment per *particle*.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] The constant is also a combination of the constants from Boyle's law, Charles's law, Avogadro's law, and Gay-Lussac's law.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] It is a physical constant that is featured in many fundamental equations in the physical sciences, such as the ideal gas law, the Arrhenius equation, and the Nernst equation.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] The gas constant is the constant of proportionality that relates the energy scale in physics to the temperature scale and the scale used for amount of substance.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] Thus, the value of the gas constant ultimately derives from historical decisions and accidents in the setting of units of energy, temperature and amount of substance.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] The Boltzmann constant and the Avogadro constant were similarly determined, which separately relate energy to temperature and particle count to amount of substance.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] Since the 2019 revision of the SI, both *N*A and *k* are defined with exact numerical values when expressed in SI units.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] As a consequence, the SI value of the molar gas constant is exact.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] Some have suggested that it might be appropriate to name the symbol *R* the **Regnault constant** in honour of the French chemist Henri Victor Regnault, whose accurate experimental data were used to calculate the early value of the constant.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] However, the origin of the letter *R* to represent the constant is elusive.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] The universal gas constant was apparently introduced independently by August Friedrich Horstmann (1873) and Dmitri Mendeleev who reported it first on 12 September 1874.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] Using his extensive measurements of the properties of gases, Mendeleev also calculated it with high precision, within 0.3% of its modern value.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] The gas constant occurs in the ideal gas law: $PV=nRT=mR_{\text{specific}}T,$ where *P* is the absolute pressure, *V* is the volume of gas, *n* is the amount of substance, *m* is the mass, and *T* is the thermodynamic temperature.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] *R*specific is the mass-specific gas constant.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] The gas constant is expressed in the same unit as molar heat.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] From the ideal gas law $PV=nRT$ we get $R={\frac {PV}{nT}},$ where *P* is pressure, *V* is volume, *n* is the amount of a given substance, and *T* is temperature.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] Area and volume are (length)2 and (length)3 respectively.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] The physical significance of *R* is work per mole per kelvin.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] Instead of a mole, the constant can be expressed by considering the normal cubic metre.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] The Boltzmann constant *k*B (alternatively *k*) may be used in place of the molar gas constant by working in pure particle count, *N*, rather than amount of substance, *n*, since $R=N_{\text{A}}k_{\text{B}},$ where *N*A is the Avogadro constant.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] For example, the ideal gas law in terms of the Boltzmann constant is $PV=Nk_{\text{B}}T,$ where *N* is the number of particles (molecules in this case), or to generalize to an inhomogeneous system the local form holds: $P=nk_{\text{B}}T,$ where *n* = *N*/*V* is the number density.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] Finally, by defining the kinetic energy associated to the temperature, $T:=k_{\text{B}}T,$ the equation becomes simply $P=nT,$ which is the form usually encountered in statistical mechanics and other branches of theoretical physics.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] As of 2006, the most precise measurement of *R* had been obtained by measuring the speed of sound *c*a(*P*, *T*) in argon at the temperature *T* of the triple point of water at different pressures *P*, and extrapolating to the zero-pressure limit *c*a(0, *T*).
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] However, following the 2019 revision of the SI, *R* now has an exact value defined in terms of other exactly defined physical constants.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] Another important relationship comes from thermodynamics.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] Mayer's relation relates the specific gas constant to the specific heat capacities for a calorically or thermally perfect gas: $R_{\text{specific}}=c_{P}-c_{V},$ where *cP* is the specific heat capacity for a constant pressure and *cV* is the specific heat capacity for a constant volume.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] It is common, especially in engineering applications, to represent the specific gas constant by the symbol *R*.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] In such cases, the universal gas constant is usually given a different symbol such as *R* to distinguish it.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] In any case, the context and/or unit of the gas constant should make it clear as to whether the universal or specific gas constant is being referred to.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] Then the molar mass of air is computed by *M*0 = *R*/*R*air = 28.964917 g/mol.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] The use of the kilomole in the unit results in an extra factor of 1000 in the constant.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] The USSA1976 acknowledges that their defined value of *R** is not consistent with the cited values for the Avogadro constant and the Boltzmann constant.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] This disparity is not a significant departure from accuracy – *R*∗ is slightly greater than 99.998% of the actual value of the constant, *R* = 8.31446261815324 J⋅mol−1⋅K−1‍ – and USSA1976 uses this value of *R*∗ for all the calculations of the standard atmosphere.
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] When using the ISO value of *R*, the calculated pressure increases by only 0.62 pascal at 11 kilometres (the equivalent of a difference of only 17.4 centimetres or 6.8 inches) and 0.292 Pa at 20 km (the equivalent of a difference of only 33.8 cm or 13.2 in).
[src:gas-constant/gas-constant] This definition was published well before the 2019 SI revision, through which the constant was given an exact value.
